{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and go to `git-scm.com/downloads`. This is the official Git website and shows download options for Windows, macOS, and Linux.",
      "title": "Go to the Official Git Website"
    },
    {
      "text": "The site detects your operating system and shows a highlighted download button. Click it to download the correct installer for your computer.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your Downloads folder and locate the file you just downloaded (e.g. `Git-2.xx.x-64-bit.exe` on Windows or a `.dmg` file on Mac). Double-click it to start.",
      "title": "Locate and Run the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, click *Next* through the setup screens, keeping the default options selected unless you have a specific reason to change them. Click *Install* when prompted.",
      "title": "Accept Default Setup Options (Windows)"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Mac, open the `.dmg` file, then double-click the `.pkg` installer inside. Follow the prompts, clicking *Continue* and *Install*, and enter your Mac password if asked.",
      "title": "Complete Installation (Mac)"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Linux, open a terminal and run `sudo apt install git` for Ubuntu/Debian or `sudo dnf install git` for Fedora. Enter your password when prompted and wait for it to finish.",
      "title": "Install via Terminal (Linux)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait for the installer to finish copying files. You should see a *Completing the Git Setup Wizard* screen on Windows or a confirmation message on Mac/Linux.",
      "title": "Wait for Installation to Finish"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click *Finish* on Windows, or close the installer window on Mac. This closes the setup process and confirms Git is installed on your system.",
      "title": "Close the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open a terminal: Command Prompt or Git Bash on Windows, Terminal on Mac, or your terminal app on Linux. This is where you'll confirm Git installed correctly.",
      "title": "Open a Terminal Window"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see output like `git version 2.42.0`, confirming Git is installed and ready to use.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you see `command not found` or a similar error, close and reopen your terminal, or restart your computer, then repeat the version check.",
      "title": "Troubleshoot if Verification Fails"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Park on flat, firm ground, engage the parking brake, and turn on hazard lights. Place wheel wedges against the tires opposite the flat to prevent rolling.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take out the spare tire, jack, and lug wrench from your trunk or storage compartment. Lay them near the flat tire for easy access.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using the lug wrench, turn each lug nut counterclockwise about a quarter turn to break it loose. Do not remove them fully yet—the tire's weight keeps them from spinning freely.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your owner's manual or the frame near the flat tire for the reinforced jack point. Position the jack head directly under this metal point, not on the plastic body panel.",
      "title": "Locate the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to raise the vehicle until the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. Go slowly and watch for the jack tipping or the car shifting.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "With the tire now off the ground, twist each loosened lug nut the rest of the way by hand and set them aside somewhere they won't roll away, like inside a hubcap.",
      "title": "Finish Removing the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire with both hands and pull it straight toward you off the wheel hub bolts. It should slide off freely once all lug nuts are removed.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the flat tire flat on the ground beside you, not standing up, so it can't roll into you or the vehicle while you work on the next steps.",
      "title": "Set the Tire Aside Safely"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Set out your French press, coarse-ground coffee, a kettle, a timer, and a stirring spoon. Coarse grounds prevent sludge and over-extraction, so avoid fine or pre-ground drip coffee if possible.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat water just off the boil, around 200°F (93°C). If you don't have a thermometer, boil water and let it sit for 30 seconds before pouring.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour a splash of hot water into the empty French press, swirl it, and discard it. This warms the glass so your coffee stays hotter longer.",
      "title": "Preheat the Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add coarse coffee grounds using a ratio of 1 gram of coffee per 15-17 grams of water (roughly 2 tablespoons per cup). Use a scale for best accuracy.",
      "title": "Measure the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour just enough hot water to saturate the grounds, about double their weight. Start your timer and let the coffee bloom for 30 seconds. You'll see bubbles form on the surface.",
      "title": "Bloom the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slowly pour the remaining hot water over the grounds until you reach your target amount. Make sure all grounds are submerged.",
      "title": "Add Remaining Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the plunger with the mesh filter on top of the press without pushing down. This traps heat and aroma while the coffee steeps.",
      "title": "Place the Lid on Top"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the coffee steep undisturbed for 4 minutes total. Avoid stirring or pressing during this time so extraction happens evenly.",
      "title": "Steep for Four Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once 4 minutes have passed, press the plunger down slowly and steadily, taking about 15-20 seconds. If you feel strong resistance, stop and pull back up slightly, then continue.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly and Steadily"
    },
    {
      "text": "Immediately pour the coffee into your cup or a carafe. Leaving it in the press causes over-extraction and a bitter taste, even after plunging.",
      "title": "Pour Right Away"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a sip. It should taste rich and balanced, not bitter or watery. If it's bitter, use a coarser grind next time; if weak, use more coffee.",
      "title": "Taste and Adjust"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear the bed of weeds, rocks, and debris. Use a hand rake or hoe to pull out roots completely so they don't regrow and compete with your tomatoes.",
      "title": "Clear Debris and Weeds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden fork or tiller to break up soil to a depth of 12 inches. Work in rows, turning the soil over so it's loose and crumbly, not compacted.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Break up any large clumps by hand or with the back of a rake. The soil should feel light and crumbly, with no dense chunks larger than a golf ball.",
      "title": "Break Up Clumps"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2 to 3 inch layer of compost or aged manure evenly over the loosened bed. This adds nutrients and improves soil texture for strong root growth.",
      "title": "Add Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden fork to mix the compost into the top 6 to 8 inches of soil. Turn the soil repeatedly until the compost is evenly blended, not sitting on the surface.",
      "title": "Mix in Amendments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scoop a handful of moist soil and squeeze it. If it crumbles apart easily, drainage is good. If it stays in a solid clump, mix in more compost or sand.",
      "title": "Check Soil Drainage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a soil pH test kit, following the package instructions. Tomatoes need a pH between 6.2 and 6.8. If the reading is off, add lime to raise pH or sulfur to lower it.",
      "title": "Test Soil pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a rake to smooth the bed surface, removing any remaining lumps and leveling the area. The bed should look flat and even from edge to edge.",
      "title": "Level the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the bed thoroughly with a hose or watering can until the soil is evenly moist but not soggy. This settles the amendments and prepares the bed for planting.",
      "title": "Water the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2 to 3 inch layer of straw or shredded leaves over the bed surface. This locks in moisture and keeps the soil ready until you plant your tomato seedlings.",
      "title": "Apply Mulch"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather your fabric, pillowcase pattern pieces, fabric scissors, straight pins, a measuring tape, and a flat surface like a large table or floor. Iron the fabric first to remove wrinkles for accurate cutting.",
      "title": "Set Up Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the fabric flat on your work surface, folded in half with right sides facing together (the printed or nicer side of the fabric touching itself). Smooth out any bumps or wrinkles.",
      "title": "Fold and Lay Out Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your pattern piece for a grainline arrow. Line up this arrow parallel to the fabric's folded edge or selvage. This keeps your pillowcase from twisting after washing.",
      "title": "Align the Grainline"
    },
    {
      "text": "Position the pattern piece on the fabric according to the layout guide in your pattern instructions. Leave a couple of inches between pieces and fabric edges for seam allowances.",
      "title": "Position the Pattern Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place pins every 3-4 inches around the edge of the pattern piece, pushing them through the paper and both fabric layers. Angle pins slightly inward so they hold the paper flat against the fabric.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern in Place"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure from the edge of the pattern to the fabric edge on multiple sides using your measuring tape. Confirm it matches the seam allowance stated in your pattern instructions, usually 1/2 inch.",
      "title": "Double-Check Measurements"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold your fabric scissors perpendicular to the table and cut slowly along the pattern's outer edge, using long, smooth strokes. Avoid lifting the fabric off the table as you cut.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Pattern Edge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut carefully around notches, curves, and any marked symbols on the pattern, following the printed line exactly. Take smaller, controlled snips around tight curves.",
      "title": "Cut Around Special Markings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove all pins from the cut fabric piece and set the pattern paper aside. Unfold the fabric piece to see the complete shape you've cut.",
      "title": "Unpin and Unfold the Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the cut piece next to the pattern to compare size and shape. It should match the pattern exactly with no jagged edges or missed cuts. Repeat these steps for each remaining pattern piece.",
      "title": "Verify the Cut Piece"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Get a tuner app, clip-on tuner, or pedal tuner ready. Sit with your guitar in playing position so you can pluck strings and turn tuning pegs at the same time.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Standard tuning from thickest to thinnest string is **E A D G B E**. Say these names aloud so you know which string you're adjusting as you go.",
      "title": "Learn the String Names"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (low E, string 6). Watch your tuner's display or needle to see if the pitch reads sharp, flat, or in tune.",
      "title": "Pluck the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the tuner shows flat (needle left or arrow left), slowly turn that string's tuning peg to tighten it. If sharp, loosen it slightly. Pluck again after each small turn.",
      "title": "Adjust the Low E Peg"
    },
    {
      "text": "Keep plucking and adjusting until the tuner shows the needle centered or the light turns green, confirming the string reads exactly *E*.",
      "title": "Confirm Low E Is In Tune"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the fifth string and check your tuner. It should read *A*. Turn the peg slowly, tightening for flat or loosening for sharp, until centered.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the fourth string. Your tuner should read *D*. Adjust the peg gradually, rechecking the display after each small turn until it centers.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the third string. The tuner should read *G*. Turn the peg slowly and recheck often until the needle or light confirms it's centered.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the second string. The tuner should read *B*. Make small peg adjustments, checking the display each time, until it's centered.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string, high E (string 1). Confirm the tuner reads *E*. Adjust gently until centered — this string is thinner and more sensitive to turns.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck all six strings again in order, low E to high E. Recheck each one on your tuner, since tightening one string can slightly shift others.",
      "title": "Recheck All Six Strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strum all six strings together. They should sound smooth and harmonious with no clashing tones. If any string drifted, retune it using your tuner until everything blends cleanly.",
      "title": "Strum to Verify Tuning"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Set your camera mode dial to **M** (Manual) so you can control ISO, aperture, and shutter speed independently. This gives you full authority over exposure instead of the camera deciding for you.",
      "title": "Switch Camera to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look through your viewfinder or LCD screen for the exposure meter, a scale with marks from -3 to +3. Press the shutter button halfway to activate it if it's not already showing.",
      "title": "Locate the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the ISO button or menu setting and set it to the lowest value your scene allows, typically *ISO 100* in bright light or *ISO 400-800* in dim conditions. Lower ISO means less grain in your photo.",
      "title": "Set Your Base ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the aperture dial or ring to choose your f-stop. Use a low number like *f/2.8* for a blurry background or a high number like *f/11* for a sharp scene front to back.",
      "title": "Choose Your Aperture (f-stop)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial and watch the exposure meter needle or indicator move. Adjust until the indicator sits at the center mark (0), showing balanced exposure.",
      "title": "Adjust Shutter Speed to Center the Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the meter reading again after your shutter speed change. If it's not centered, increase shutter speed to darken the image or decrease it to brighten the image.",
      "title": "Confirm the Meter Reads Zero"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your shutter speed drops below 1/60 second while handholding, raise your ISO instead to avoid blur, then recheck the meter and readjust shutter speed if needed.",
      "title": "Watch for Camera Shake Risk"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button fully to capture the image, then view it on your LCD screen. Check that details are visible in both bright and dark areas, not washed out or too dark.",
      "title": "Take a Test Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the playback button, then zoom in using the magnify button to inspect brightness and detail. If the histogram graph is available, look for a curve that isn't pressed against either edge.",
      "title": "Review the Histogram or Zoomed Image"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image looks too bright, decrease exposure by choosing a faster shutter speed, smaller aperture (higher f-number), or lower ISO. Retake the shot and check again.",
      "title": "Fix an Overexposed Image"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image looks too dark, increase exposure by choosing a slower shutter speed, wider aperture (lower f-number), or higher ISO. Retake the shot and check again.",
      "title": "Fix an Underexposed Image"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once your test shot shows good detail in highlights and shadows with the meter near zero, you've achieved proper exposure. Note these settings for similar lighting conditions going forward.",
      "title": "Confirm Final Exposure Settings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, toes turned out slightly (about 15 degrees). Keep your weight balanced evenly across both feet, not shifted to your toes or heels.",
      "title": "Set Your Foot Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Raise both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height, or clasp hands together at your chest. This counterbalances your body as you squat down.",
      "title": "Position Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull your shoulders back and down, and tighten your core as if bracing for a punch. Keep your chest lifted throughout the entire movement.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core and Chest"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and push your hips back, as if sitting into a chair behind you. Keep your knees tracking over your toes, not caving inward.",
      "title": "Initiate the Hip Hinge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor, or as low as your mobility allows while keeping your heels flat on the ground.",
      "title": "Lower to Proper Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look in a mirror or record yourself from the side. Your knees should stay behind or in line with your toes, not extending far past them.",
      "title": "Check Your Knee Alignment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Keep your entire foot, including your heels, pressed firmly into the floor. If your heels lift up, shift your weight back slightly.",
      "title": "Keep Heels Grounded"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look straight ahead at a fixed point, keeping your neck in line with your spine. Avoid dropping your chin or looking down at the floor.",
      "title": "Maintain a Neutral Head Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drive through your heels and mid-foot to push your hips forward and up, returning to standing. Squeeze your glutes at the top to finish the rep.",
      "title": "Push Back Up to Standing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Do 5 slow, controlled squats using all the checkpoints above. Pause at the bottom for one second each time to check your knee and chest position.",
      "title": "Practice a Full Set"
    },
    {
      "text": "Film yourself from the front and side. Check that your knees don't cave in, your back stays flat, and your depth is consistent across every rep.",
      "title": "Record and Review Your Form"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Coloque na bancada: farinha, fermento biológico seco ou fresco, açúcar, sal, água ou leite morno e manteiga. Tenha uma tigela grande e um pano limpo à mão antes de começar.",
      "title": "Reúna os Ingredientes e Utensílios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aqueça a água ou leite até ficar morno ao toque, entre 35°C e 40°C. Não deixe muito quente, pois isso mata o fermento. Teste pingando uma gota no pulso.",
      "title": "Aqueça o Líquido"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture o fermento, uma pitada de açúcar e o líquido morno. Misture bem com uma colher até dissolver completamente.",
      "title": "Dissolva o Fermento no Líquido"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deixe a mistura descansar por 10 minutos sem mexer. Você deve ver espuma e bolhas na superfície, sinal de que o fermento está vivo e ativo.",
      "title": "Aguarde a Ativação do Fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Numa tigela grande, misture a farinha e o sal. Faça um buraco no centro da farinha para receber os líquidos depois.",
      "title": "Misture os Ingredientes Secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a mistura de fermento ativado no centro da farinha. Adicione a manteiga derretida ou óleo, se a receita pedir.",
      "title": "Adicione o Fermento à Farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com uma colher ou as mãos, misture tudo até formar uma massa grossa e pegajosa, sem partes secas de farinha visíveis na tigela.",
      "title": "Misture Até Formar a Massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Espalhe um pouco de farinha na bancada e coloque a massa sobre ela. Isso evita que a massa fique presa na superfície durante a sova.",
      "title": "Transfira para Superfície Enfarinhada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Empurre a massa para frente com a palma da mão, dobre-a de volta e gire 90 graus. Repita esse movimento continuamente por cerca de 10 minutos.",
      "title": "Sove a Massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pare de sovar quando a massa estiver lisa, elástica e não pegajosa. Ao esticar um pedaço, ele deve ficar fino sem rasgar facilmente.",
      "title": "Verifique o Ponto da Massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa sovada em uma bola redonda, puxando as bordas para baixo e apertando levemente por cima até ficar firme e uniforme.",
      "title": "Modele a Massa em Bola"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a bola de massa em uma tigela levemente untada e cubra com um pano limpo ou plástico filme. A massa está pronta para crescer.",
      "title": "Cubra a Massa Preparada"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Antes de empezar, junta una llave ajustable, un destornillador plano y de cruz, pinzas, cinta de teflón, y un juego de repuesto de arandelas u O-rings para grifos.",
      "title": "Reúne las herramientas necesarias"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca la llave de paso debajo del fregadero, generalmente dos válvulas pequeñas. Gira ambas en sentido de las agujas del reloj hasta que se detengan por completo.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre el grifo para confirmar que no sale agua. Si aún gotea algo, cierra más fuerte las válvulas de paso hasta que el flujo se detenga totalmente.",
      "title": "Verifica que el agua esté cortada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un trapo o tapón en el desagüe del fregadero para evitar que tornillos pequeños se caigan por el drenaje mientras trabajas.",
      "title": "Protege el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca una tapa decorativa en la manija, hazla palanca con un destornillador plano para retirarla. Debajo verás un tornillo que sujeta la manija.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa de la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa el destornillador para quitar el tornillo debajo de la tapa. Luego tira suavemente de la manija hacia arriba para separarla del cuerpo del grifo.",
      "title": "Quita el tornillo y la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con la llave ajustable, gira la tuerca de empaque en sentido contrario a las agujas del reloj para aflojarla y retirarla por completo.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Jala hacia afuera el cartucho o vástago que queda expuesto. Anota su orientación para poder colocarlo igual al reinstalarlo.",
      "title": "Extrae el cartucho o vástago"
    },
    {
      "text": "Observa el O-ring de goma y la arandela en la punta del cartucho. Si están agrietados, endurecidos o desgastados, ahí está la causa del goteo.",
      "title": "Inspecciona las piezas de goma"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con las pinzas, retira el O-ring o la arandela dañada. Coloca la pieza nueva del mismo tamaño en la misma posición exacta que tenía la original.",
      "title": "Reemplaza el O-ring o arandela"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si el grifo tiene un asiento de válvula visible y con marcas, retíralo con una llave especial para asientos y coloca uno nuevo del mismo tamaño.",
      "title": "Cambia el asiento de válvula si aplica"
    },
    {
      "text": "Envuelve las roscas metálicas con dos o tres vueltas de cinta de teflón en sentido de las agujas del reloj antes de volver a armar las piezas.",
      "title": "Aplica cinta de teflón en las roscas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el cartucho o vástago en la misma orientación que tenía antes. Debe encajar suavemente sin forzarlo demasiado.",
      "title": "Reinstala el cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la tuerca de empaque y gírala en sentido de las agujas del reloj con la llave ajustable hasta que quede firme, sin apretar en exceso.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vuelve a colocar la manija sobre el vástago, alineándola en su posición original, luego inserta y aprieta el tornillo que la sujeta.",
      "title": "Coloca la manija y el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Presiona la tapa decorativa sobre la manija hasta que encaje con un clic, cubriendo el tornillo por completo.",
      "title": "Cierra la tapa decorativa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Regresa debajo del fregadero y gira ambas válvulas de paso en sentido contrario a las agujas del reloj para abrir el suministro de agua.",
      "title": "Abre el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre el grifo despacio y observa el chorro. Debe salir agua limpia y continua sin goteo desde la base ni desde el pico.",
      "title": "Prueba el grifo por fugas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deja el grifo abierto un minuto y revisa debajo del fregadero con una toalla seca. Si no hay humedad, la reparación fue exitosa.",
      "title": "Confirma que no haya fugas debajo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before saving, look at the title bar or tab of your document. If you see a dot, asterisk, or the word *unsaved*, it means you have changes that still need to be saved.",
      "title": "Check for Unsaved Changes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **File** menu in the top-left corner of the application window. A dropdown menu will appear with several options including *Save*, *Save As*, and *Open*.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
